This analysis documents U.S. racial/ethnic and gender differences in life 
expectancies with different self-reported sleep durations among adults aged 50 
and older. We used self-reported sleep duration and linked mortality information 
from the 2004-2015 National Health Interview Survey (n = 145,015) to calculate 
Sullivan Method Lifetables for life expectancies with different self-reported 
sleep duration states: short (≤6 hours), optimal (seven to 8 hours), and long 
(≥9 hours) sleep duration per-day by race/ethnicity and gender. Non-Hispanic 
Black men (35.8%, 95% CI: 34.8%-36.8%) and women (36.5%, 95% CI: 35.7%-37.1%) 
exhibited the highest proportion of years lived with short sleep duration 
followed by Hispanic men (31.1%, 95% CI: 29.9%-32.3%) and women (34.1%, 95% CI: 
33.1%-35.1%) and Non-Hispanic White men (25.8%, 95% CI: 25.4%-26.2%) and women 
(27.4%, 95% CI: 27.0%-27.7%). These results highlight how race/ethnic inequality 
in sleep duration and life expectancy are intertwined among older adults in the 
U.S.

